# <type>(<scope>): <summary>   (imperative, ≤50 chars)
#
# Body (wrap at 72): what changed and why; note breaking changes / migration.
# Link the spec or issue.
#
# Examples:
#   feat(core): derive the tier from the diff with --auto
#   fix(checks): stop lifecycle reddening a fresh draft
#   docs(roadmap): bounded slug-keyed worklist
#   ci: pin release-please to v5
#
# Types (feat/fix change the version; the rest do not):
#   feat     - new behaviour or capability          (minor bump)
#   fix      - bug fix                               (patch bump)
#   docs     - documentation only
#   chore    - maintenance, dependencies, tooling
#   refactor - restructuring, no behaviour change
#   test     - tests only
#   ci       - CI / workflows
#   build    - build system / toolchain
#   perf     - performance
#   revert   - revert a prior commit
#
# Scopes (optional; one of the three top-level areas):
#   core        - the gate: binary, Go packages, and shipped checks (core/)
#   bindings    - the Claude plugin and the open-code binding (bindings/)
#   governance  - this repo's own governance, roadmap, and specs (leitwerk/)
#
# Breaking change: add ! after type/scope (e.g. feat(core)!:) or a
# "BREAKING CHANGE:" footer. Pre-1.0 this bumps the minor, not the major.
#
# Because PRs are squash-merged, the PR title must also be a valid Conventional
# Commit (the semantic-pr check enforces it).
